_**Age Ain 't Nothing but a Number**_ is the debut studio album by American
[R&B](/wiki/Contemporary_R%26B "Contemporary R&B") recording artist
[Aaliyah](/wiki/Aaliyah "Aaliyah"), released under [Jive](/wiki/Jive_Records
"Jive Records") and [Blackground Records](/wiki/Blackground_Records
"Blackground Records") on May 24, 1994, in the United States. After being
signed by her uncle [Barry Hankerson](/wiki/Barry_Hankerson "Barry
Hankerson"), Aaliyah was introduced to recording artist and producer [R.
Kelly](/wiki/R._Kelly "R. Kelly"). He became her [mentor](/wiki/Mentor
"Mentor"), as well as the lead songwriter and producer of the album. The duo
recorded the album at the [Chicago Recording
Company](/wiki/Chicago_Recording_Company "Chicago Recording Company") in
[Chicago](/wiki/Chicago "Chicago"), [Illinois](/wiki/Illinois "Illinois"). The
album featured two hit singles, including the top ten-charting "[Back &
Forth](/wiki/Back_%26_Forth_\(Aaliyah_song\) "Back & Forth \(Aaliyah song\)")"
and "[At Your Best (You Are
Love)](/wiki/At_Your_Best_\(You_Are_Love\)#Aaliyah_version "At Your Best \(You
Are Love\)")"; both singles were certified
[Gold](/wiki/Music_recording_sales_certification "Music recording sales
certification") by the [Recording Industry Association of
America](/wiki/Recording_Industry_Association_of_America "Recording Industry
Association of America") (RIAA). One additional single followed in the US:
"[Age Ain't Nothing but a
Number](/wiki/Age_Ain%27t_Nothing_but_a_Number_\(song\) "Age Ain't Nothing but
a Number \(song\)")". Two more singles were released internationally after
"Age Ain't Nothing But a Number": "[Down with the
Clique](/wiki/Down_with_the_Clique "Down with the Clique")" and "[The Thing I
Like](/wiki/The_Thing_I_Like "The Thing I Like")".

_Age Ain 't Nothing But a Number_ received generally favorable reviews from
critics. Many noted Aaliyah's vocal ability and praised the lyrical content.
Aaliyah was credited for redefining [R&B](/wiki/Contemporary_R%26B
"Contemporary R&B") by blending her voice with Kelly's [new jack
swing](/wiki/New_jack_swing "New jack swing"). The album peaked at number 18
on the [_Billboard_ 200](/wiki/Billboard_200 "Billboard 200") and sold over
three million copies in the United States.[2] The album was certified Gold in
Canada by the [Canadian Recording Industry
Association](/wiki/Canadian_Recording_Industry_Association "Canadian Recording
Industry Association") (CRIA) and Gold in the United Kingdom by the [British
Phonographic Industry](/wiki/British_Phonographic_Industry "British
Phonographic Industry") (BPI) to date. The album has sold over six million
copies worldwide.[3]

## Background and
recording[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Age_Ain%27t_Nothing_but_a_Number&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: Background and recording")]

After [Barry Hankerson](/wiki/Barry_Hankerson "Barry Hankerson"), Aaliyah's
uncle, signed a distribution deal with [Jive Records](/wiki/Jive_Records "Jive
Records"), he signed her to his [Blackground
Records](/wiki/Blackground_Records "Blackground Records") label at the age of
12.[4][5] Hankerson then introduced her to recording artist and producer [R.
Kelly](/wiki/R._Kelly "R. Kelly").[6] He became Aaliyah's mentor, as well as
lead [songwriter](/wiki/Songwriter "Songwriter") and producer of the
album.[7][8] Aaliyah and Kelly began recording the album in 1993 when she was
14.[5] The duo recorded the first song, "Old School", at the [Chicago
Recording Company](/wiki/Chicago_Recording_Company "Chicago Recording
Company") in [Chicago](/wiki/Chicago "Chicago"), [Illinois](/wiki/Illinois
"Illinois").[9][10] While recording the album, Kelly coached her as they
worked several hours in the studio. She often sang the songs multiple times in
order to achieve "excellence".[11] He claimed that Aaliyah was "one of the
best young artists" he had worked with.[10]

## Musical
content[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Age_Ain%27t_Nothing_but_a_Number&action=edit&section=2
"Edit section: Musical content")]

Aaliyah sang her songs in a [falsetto](/wiki/Falsetto "Falsetto"). She felt
that the songs "came at you kind of tough, a bit edgy, hip-hop, but the vocals
can be very soothing".[12] She went on to say, "lyrically I want things to be
different."[12]

## Marketing and
promotion[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Age_Ain%27t_Nothing_but_a_Number&action=edit&section=3
"Edit section: Marketing and promotion")]

A month before the release of the debut single, "[Back &
Forth](/wiki/Back_%26_Forth_\(Aaliyah_song\) "Back & Forth \(Aaliyah
song\)")", Aaliyah attended the Urban Network's "Power Jam" conference, where
she was introduced and "received warmly".[10] "Back & Forth" peaked at number
five on the [_Billboard_ Hot 100](/wiki/Billboard_Hot_100 "Billboard Hot 100")
while topping the [Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs](/wiki/Hot_R%26B/Hip-Hop_Songs "Hot
R&B/Hip-Hop Songs") chart for three weeks.[13] The song was certified
[Gold](/wiki/Music_recording_sales_certification "Music recording sales
certification") by the [RIAA](/wiki/Recording_Industry_Association_of_America
"Recording Industry Association of America").[14] The second single, "[At Your
Best (You Are Love)](/wiki/At_Your_Best_\(You_Are_Love\)#Aaliyah_version "At
Your Best \(You Are Love\)")", peaked at number six on the _Billboard_ Hot 100
and was also certified Gold by the RIAA.[13][14] In promotion for the album,
Aaliyah embarked on a world tour that lasted from 1994 to 1995, she toured
through the US, Europe, Japan and South Africa[15][16][17]

_Age Ain 't Nothing But a Number_ received generally favorable reviews from
[music critics](/wiki/Music_critic "Music critic").[_[citation
needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed "Wikipedia:Citation needed")_] Some
writers noted that Aaliyah's "silky vocals" and "sultry voice" blended with
Kelly's [new jack swing](/wiki/New_jack_swing "New jack swing") helped define
R&B in the 1990s.[20][22] Her sound was also compared to that of female
quartet [En Vogue](/wiki/En_Vogue "En Vogue").[20][23] Christopher John Farley
of _[Time](/wiki/Time_\(magazine\) "Time \(magazine\)")_ magazine described
the album as a "beautifully restrained work", noting that Aaliyah's "girlish,
breathy vocals rode calmly on R.Kelly's rough beats".[24] [Stephen Thomas
Erlewine](/wiki/Stephen_Thomas_Erlewine "Stephen Thomas Erlewine") of
[Allmusic](/wiki/Allmusic "Allmusic") felt that the album had its "share of
filler", but described the singles as "slyly seductive".[18] He also claimed
that the songs on the album were "frequently better" than that of Kelly's
first studio album, _[12 Play](/wiki/12_Play "12 Play")_.[18]

The album debuted at number 24 on the [_Billboard_ 200](/wiki/Billboard_200
"Billboard 200") chart, selling 74,000 copies in its first week.[25][26] The
album ultimately peaked at number 18 on the chart.[27] It sold three million
copies in the United States and 6 million copies worldwide.[14][28] [29] In
Canada, the album debuted at number 29,[30] peaked at number 20[31] and spent
25 weeks at the chart,[32] selling over 50,000 copies and was certified gold
by the [CRIA](/wiki/Canadian_Recording_Industry_Association "Canadian
Recording Industry Association").[33] It also peaked at number 44 on the
[Dutch Albums Chart](/wiki/Dutch_Albums_Chart "Dutch Albums Chart");[34] it
peaked at number 23 on the [UK Albums Chart](/wiki/UK_Albums_Chart "UK Albums
Chart"), where it was certified Gold by the
[BPI](/wiki/British_Phonographic_Industry "British Phonographic
Industry").[35][36]
